# Amex Fraud & Risk Anomaly Detection

## Business Problem
Card issuers need to identify suspicious transaction patterns quickly to limit financial losses and protect customers, while avoiding overly aggressive flagging that disrupts legitimate spend. This project analyzes transaction-level data to detect anomalous patterns and flag potential risk, balancing detection sensitivity with false-positive impact on genuine customers.

## Dataset
**Source 1:** [Credit Card Fraud Detection](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/mlg-ulb/creditcardfraud) (Kaggle, by mlg-ulb)
284,807 anonymized European transactions over 2 days, with 492 confirmed fraud cases (highly imbalanced — 0.172% fraud rate).

**Source 2:** [Credit Card Transactions Dataset](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/priyamchoksi/credit-card-transactions-dataset) (Kaggle, by priyamchoksi)
Transaction-level data with merchant, category, location, and cardholder details — used for SQL-based rule logic since fields are human-readable (unlike the PCA-anonymized fraud dataset).

See `data/README.md` for download instructions.

## Objective
Use SQL to flag rule-based anomalies (spend spikes, unusual merchant categories, geography mismatches) and use Python to apply statistical anomaly detection (z-score thresholds, rolling averages) on labeled fraud data — without building a full ML classification
